metadata.name: In Due Time #29
metadata.description:
“In Due Time” is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht’s mastery of line and Vittoria’s notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria’s poem for the collection:

“In Due Time”
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

To save a high-resolution image for printing, click “open” under the image on the page for your token, and then hit:

Digits “1” through “9” to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: Los Osos 2422 #2353
metadata.description:
# Los Osos 2422

I was working on the next EmProps release when accidentally I opened a link to a bear utopic civilization through their existing metaverse. Or should I say "metabears"?

Enter Los Osos 2422. 

Four hundred years into the future bears live in a peaceful civilization heavily inspired by the generative art movement of our times. They are organized in districts that are sustained by bamboo, salmon, berries, and art! Los Osos are black, grizzly, panda, and polar, yet there are no distinctions between species; it's not like they were humans. 

They have different occupations but frequently bears change jobs giving birth to the most eclectic looks.

I took my sketchbook out to capture what I could and started drawing but my presence pissed them off. Ninjas, luchadores, and even a cybearpunk forced me to escape.  Is that a live gummy bear or am I just hungry? The story will continue...

-- 

Los Osos 2422 is a PFP art piece composed of 320 hand-made drawings made as an homage to the nascent generative art current fueled by Tezos blockchain technology in 2022. It features hundreds of references to artists and pieces in several generative and non-generative fields.

The project combines the assets together using a custom open-source algorithm that allows them to stack with the positioning in front and behind the character to create possibilities like shirt collars or hats, dynamic tinting to have hoodies or glasses with different colors, exceptions to give them laser eyes or a green apple in front of the face, complex set-ups to have different versions for some of the outfits, and chance control to allow precise control over the features.

--

Press 'S' on the keyboard to save it as an 1800 x 1800 pixels PNG.

metadata.name: Entropes #5
metadata.description:
Entropes is an abstract generative art project consisting of patterns and textures made with a heuristic rectangle packing algorithm. It’s a blend of shapes, geometry and colour. It draws notable inspiration from the Bauhaus art style. All these attributes are fused to form aesthetics that create diversity while maintaining cohesiveness across this body of work.

_____________________________________________________________________________________

The details go down to the very last pixel and outputs can be saved right from the browser at a full resolution of 6400 x 9600 pixels which ensures the quality holds up across majority of displays and different print sizes.

_____________________________________________________________________________________

Programmed entirely using p5js.

_____________________________________________________________________________________

A project by Kamau Kamau and Ian Wright

metadata.name: Lineage #207
metadata.description:
Lineage is a collaboration between Tim Maxwell and Twistie that attempts to bridge the gap between traditional and generative art.
256 outputs are generated using 100% JavaScript + p5js, written by Twistie, in the distinctive style of Tim Maxwell. The code tries to replicate not only the style, but also the process and inaccuracies that go into a drawing.

Each iteration has a unique title. 
All 256 rendered outputs and their respective titles will be displayed in high quality on https://twistie.org/lineage. 

10 lucky owners will have their iteration hand drawn and signed. They will each receive the physical 1/1 as well as an NFT version.

Press 's' on keyboard to save in high-res. This is how the art is intended to be viewed.

Hardware acceleration on Chromium-based browsers can impact performance!

metadata.name: Mounds 3 #178
metadata.description:
"Mounds 3" is part of an ongoing series of experiments combining hand-drawn "mounds" and turning them into something unexpected. The p5.js sketch has up to 172 different "mound" illustrations to pick from to build the scene.⁠
⁠
Please be patient. It will take a few seconds for the scene to render; a lot is going on under the hood.⁠ The sketch will load in layers, and the console will log "Done rendering!" when the whole scene is done loading.
⁠
This token was handmade with pens, markers, ink, and p5.js.⁠
⁠
I drew these squiggles between August 29th - September 6th, 2022, with a combination of pens, markers, and brushes in various sketchbooks. The sketches are scanned and separated in Photoshop.⁠

I hope you enjoy this mint as much as I did making it! See https://natenolting.com/2022/09/06/mounds-3/ for more details on this project.

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: scale to print size @ 3000px x 3000px

metadata.name: One Eleven (are Better Than Thirty) #108
metadata.description:
One Eleven (are Better Than Thirty), is the fourth installment of One Eleven, a periodical experiment.

Even though Andy Warhols work is not cc0, the Mona Lisa is. So yes, this is inspired, heavily, by Andy Warhol, most notably the piece Thirty are Better Than One, but uses no component of it. Let’s call it an homage. We also feel that if Andy were alive today, they would embrace cc0. Art is just about fame and exposure anyways, right?

And yes, initially we wanted to make a grid that had exactly 111 Mona Lisas on it, but tbh, it looked terrible. They were too small, and the iterations were too same-y. So, instead, each iteration of this will have 111 pages, each with varying amounts of Mona Lisas. You just click the art and a new page appears. 111 for each one minted. Then it loops back around.

So, really, this collection gives you 111 pieces for the price of 1, which is free. Pretty good deal.

How do you get on the list? Read below:

Collectors of the genesis One Eleven (#12743) are on the allow list for all One Eleven collections, this one included. A bit before minting is enabled, the list will be updated granting one reserve for each iteration held. So, buy one before this drops. Any procured after the scheduled release time will not get you on the list, but will be considered once the reserves are lifted. Reserves will be lifted after 111 hours, give or take.

As a bonus, whoever holds One Eleven #1 will receive #1 of this collection as an airdrop. The project will be disabled until that happens, but should occur right around the scheduled time.

Half of the royalties for all One Eleven collections will be shared with the minter.

This collection uses the One Eleven SDK, which makes embedding One Eleven into FXHash collections very simple. You can use it if you like for your projects, as it is cc0. Talk to us on twitter if you'd like to release it as a collab.

More info: an0n.wtf/sdk

I'm sorry this is so complicated. When it started, it seemed simpler.

metadata.name: Obliques #102
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Up Above #13
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the feeling of insignificance. This feeling, which we all share and feel at some points in our lives is often referred to as negative. But I feel quite the contrary, this feeling is quite beautiful, as it shows small parts together can form something big.

We are but a speck in the universe, like a grain of sand on a beach, like a single drop of water in an ocean, like a single leaf on a tree. But together we are a forest, a river, a sea. Together we are the universe.

Feel free to explore this piece for as long as you want, and feel free to export it in any way you like, and use it for thing like prints, and, of course, I'd love to know about them :)

---

To export your iteration, click the menu bar at the bottom of the screen and press either the "Export current" or "Export custom" button.

metadata.name: Sub Section Patina #380
metadata.description:
"Sub Section Patina" is inspired by street art and the marks and layering from that art form. If you zoom in on a small section of a wall that artists have marked, sprayed paint, and plastered with posters, some beautiful effects start to happen.

While the "Sub Section Patina" layers are building up, there is a tendency to destroy the layers below. The layering is similar to a wall many street artists have contributed. Sometimes just a section will be covered and filled with something else. Sometimes large areas of the canvas are covered up. Other layers will be put on top of one another, creating a new chaotic image. 

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
substack/point-in-polygon

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

metadata.name: sunz #40
metadata.description:
Your spaceship enters a wormhole and emerges in a distant solar system. The crew is surprised to find that the star system is full of metal plates, which may be the remains of a long-destroyed civilization. They soon realize that they are in an alien shipyard. The crew must find a way to escape before the aliens find them.

This NFT has 5 features with unique distributions:

"debris chunks": do the metal plates form chunks of shapes?
"density": how many metal plates occur?
"mirror": are the plates arranged in a mirrored fashion?
"sun size": how big is the sun you are facing?
"speed": how quick is the spaceship flying?

In addition, there are a lot of unique traits that have not been exposed as a feature, but still contribute to the overall scene and provide a distinctive style. For example each scene has it's own soundscape of composed ambient drones. Another one is a special color grading technique that is selected.

Some infos:
- click the canvas or press h/i to get an info window (including FPS)
- press "S" to toggle a mysterious samples setting
- press "C" to toggle the chromatic abberation effect
- press "M" to toggle music
- press "+" to increase PPI for screenshots
- press "space" to take screenshots (PPI * current viewport)

You need a good computer and a modern browser like Chrome to run this simulation with decent FPS.

metadata.name: what's left of what's left #12
metadata.description:
"The images is not a closed field of knowledge; it is a whirling, centrifugal field. It is not a fiedl of knowledge like any other; it is a movement demanding all the anthropogical aspects of being and time" Didi-Huberman

Continuing in the experimentation of photography and generative art.

What's left of what's left ... Seeks to take the reflection beyond the simple superimposition of images, highlighting the "human" x "machine" interaction.

The areas of light, fog and shadows present us with image clippings in a large tangle of visual reflections.

The algorithm builds unique images from the combination of different layers, according to a bank of photographs extracted from my own collection. In total, there are six layers containing 10 photographs each, in addition to a base layer containing 20 photos of urban fragments.

In addition, the code implements, in a random and semi-autonomous way, some adaptations such as masking, colorization, rotation and blending modes for specific layers.

* Features
Place - Where have i been. 20 distinct urban fragments;
Mode - “Color” 80% or “B&W” 20%;
Zone - “Amazon” 25%; “Mist” and “Terracotta” 20%, “Old Sky” 15%; and “Ocher” and “Golden” 10%.
Invert - 2.5%

"In a sense of overlapping past/future, not as an idea of ​​current time, but as places of memory dispute. This "non-place", traversed by layers, is solidified in the images, almost like a truce from the endless war of this inconstancy.
there is no winner" Raffa Gomes

Generative Token by of Morbeck for fxhash

august 21, 2022

metadata.name: Snell's Artifacts #42
metadata.description:
Snell's artifacts are imaginary geometric objects created using Snell's and Descartes' laws of optics that define the behavior of a ray of light passing from one transparent medium to another.

By applying these laws to extreme parameters, beyond what the real world is capable of producing and with a high level of variability, we open the door to a new world.

In order to keep some control over this extreme and crazy world, the grid within which the rays evolve is divided into several squares. Each of these squares limits the grid settings at that location.

In order to be able to generate a Snell Artifact, 1 to 6 million rays are created. It may take a while. So be patient while these radii are calculated.




Keyboard commands:
[S]: Saves a PNG image of 4000x4000 pixels without glow filter
[SHIFT + S]: Saves a 4000x4000 pixel PNG image and applies a glow filter (may take a long time depending on your system)

URL parameters:
Add the parameter size=N to generate an image of NxN pixels (glow effect will be disabled by default)
Add the parameter glow=true to apply a glow effect to the image




Artist: Estienne
July 2022

metadata.name: Symbology437 #14
metadata.description:
Abstract, distorted compositions using symbols from the original IBM VGA codepage 437 character set. The symbols were created in code as bitmaps, scaled, and then drawn onto the canvas. The shading is based on the characters and sets from ANSI and ASCII art styles. 

There are 4 main types of outputs:
- Abstracts, 50%
- Random characters, 25%
- One of 16 preset character layouts, 25%
- One of 16 custom symbol PFP styles that will be 10% of the total outputs

For abstracts, there are several main styles created from layering different base shapes: circles, filled circles, rectangles, flow field lines, and rain-like streaks.

Color combinations include monochromatic, green or amber, dark mode, and multicolor.

Press 's' to save the image. The size is 2318x3000px, and for PFPs, the size is 3000x3000px.

metadata.name: ARAUCO #9
metadata.description:
The Araucaria Araucana, also known as pewén, is a sacred tree for the Mapuche and an emblem of Chile. With an origin dating back 260 million years to the Triassic period, it is part of the oldest forests on the planet. These ancient trees are endangered due to logging, forest fires, and grazing.

ARAUCO is a tribute to araucarias and Mapuche iconography. Incorporating elements such as the Kultrung, the Wünelfe star, and the staggered cross Ngümin, the work displays a typical landscape of southern Chile with the Andes Mountains in the background and the native forest. 

–

Press 's' to export a 4960x7016 PNG file suitable for A2 printing at 300 dpi.

Made with p5js.

Patricio Isaías, September 2022
